responsible for male pubic hair development at Tanner stage 4?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dehydroepiandrosterone","Testosterone","Follicle stimulating hormone","Growth hormone","Luteinizing hormone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe development of pubic hair (adrenarche) is primarily driven by adrenal androgens, particularly \u003Cstrong\u003Edehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA)\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs independently of gonadal development and can precede other pubertal changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Etestosterone\u003C/strong\u003E plays a crucial role in male sexual development and maturation, it is not the primary hormone responsible for pubic hair growth. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eluteinising hormone\u003C/strong\u003E are important for testicular development and testosterone production but do not directly cause pubic hair growth. \u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is important for overall growth during puberty but does not specifically drive pubic hair development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETanner stage 4 pubic hair appears as adult-type hair that spreads to the medial thighs but has not yet spread up the linea alba to the umbilicus. This development is part of the normal progression of secondary sexual characteristics during puberty.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pubic hair development (adrenarche) is primarily driven by adrenal androgens, particularly dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA).","Tanner stage 4 pubic hair in males appears as adult-type hair that spreads to medial thighs but not up linea alba.","While testosterone contributes to sexual maturation, adrenal androgens are the main driver of pubic hair development."],"references":["Miller BS, Sarafoglou K, Addo OY. Development of Tanner Stage-Age Adjusted CDC Height Curves for Research and Clinical Applications. J Endocr Soc. 2020 Jul 17;4(9):bvaa098. doi: 10.1210/jendso/bvaa098. PMID: 32818164; PMCID: PMC7426000","Emmanuel M, Bokor BR. Tanner Stages. [Updated 2022 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470280/","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60110"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:14:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:58:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8962"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74616"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group